    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i also saw a section about how blockages can mess up the readings. what kind of stuff usually gets stuck in there and causes issues?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The most common culprits for clogging a pitot tube are ice, debris from snowstorms, and sometimes even insects or bird droppings if the bird strikes the sensor directly. Ice is particularly dangerous in cold and rainy conditions because it can quickly freeze the tube shut, causing the airspeed indicator to read zero or fluctuate wildly. To prevent these issues, pilots regularly flush the tube with compressed air during routine maintenance checks, but even with cleaning, the tiny orifice is very susceptible to external obstructions.",
